BILL NYE: What chemistry?

00:02:31.830 --> 00:02:32.387
Paleo?

00:02:32.387 --> 00:02:33.220
DANA HAN-KLEIN: Bio.

00:02:33.220 --> 00:02:34.050
BILL NYE: Biochemistry.

00:02:34.050 --> 00:02:34.550
DANA HAN-KLEIN: A little bit.

00:02:34.550 --> 00:02:35.050
Touched on it.

00:02:35.050 --> 00:02:37.005
It was high school, so
it wasn't-- we didn't get

00:02:37.005 --> 00:02:37.140
detailed.

00:02:37.140 --> 00:02:38.100
BILL NYE: So there's water.

00:02:38.100 --> 00:02:38.405
There's a lot of water.

00:02:38.405 --> 00:02:40.130
DANA HAN-KLEIN: There's a
lot of water involved, lots

00:02:40.130 --> 00:02:41.390
of bathroom passes and-- no.

00:02:43.830 --> 00:02:44.330
No.

00:02:44.330 --> 00:02:46.780
But it was an attempt
to kind of introduce us

00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:50.549
to evolution and biodiversity,
and we had a unit [INAUDIBLE]

00:02:50.549 --> 00:02:51.090
at one point.

00:02:51.090 --> 00:02:51.220
BILL NYE: Good, good.

00:02:51.220 --> 00:02:52.110
Like the environment.

00:02:52.110 --> 00:02:53.490
The science of the environment.

00:02:53.490 --> 00:02:55.990
DANA HAN-KLEIN: The science of
the environment, if you will.

00:02:55.990 --> 00:02:56.830
BILL NYE: Brilliant.

00:02:56.830 --> 00:02:57.663
DANA HAN-KLEIN: Yes.

00:02:57.663 --> 00:03:01.110
But so it's not something
that's in your immediate field.

00:03:01.110 --> 00:03:04.950
And I feel like you took it
upon yourself as an educator

00:03:04.950 --> 00:03:06.160
to go out and do this.

00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:08.877
So can you tell me about
some of the highlights

00:03:08.877 --> 00:03:10.460
of your own education
that brought you

00:03:10.460 --> 00:03:12.150
to this point in time
where you're like,

00:03:12.150 --> 00:03:13.670
I am on a mission to educate.

00:03:16.220 --> 00:03:19.250
BILL NYE: That's
very good, Bill.

00:03:19.250 --> 00:03:21.900
I had Carl Sagan for astronomy.

00:03:21.900 --> 00:03:23.800
I just took one class from him.

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:26.010
I was by no means
his star student.

00:03:26.010 --> 00:03:27.760
I was just like some guy.

00:03:27.760 --> 00:03:30.407
But he had a huge effect on me.

00:03:30.407 --> 00:03:32.490
Is there anybody here--
it's fine-- have you never

00:03:32.490 --> 00:03:34.600
heard of Carl Sagan?

00:03:34.600 --> 00:03:36.285
That's remarkable.

00:03:36.285 --> 00:03:37.660
DANA HAN KLEIN:
We are at Google.

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:38.660
BILL NYE: Yeah, yeah.

00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:41.100
But people are from other
parts of the world and so on.

00:03:41.100 --> 00:03:44.330
So he was a very
influential guy.

00:03:44.330 --> 00:03:46.960
And my high school physics
teacher was hugely influential,

00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:48.480
George Lang.

00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:50.840
And I had a fabulous
sixth grade teacher.

00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:53.500
And these people just--you know,
you spend more time with them

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:55.550
than you do with your parents.

00:03:55.550 --> 00:03:58.790
And so this is why
teaching as a profession

00:03:58.790 --> 00:04:00.470
is an important thing.

00:04:00.470 --> 00:04:02.804
Nobody wants to pay for it,
but it's an important thing.

00:04:02.804 --> 00:04:04.220
DANA HAN-KLEIN:
What would you say

00:04:04.220 --> 00:04:06.550
makes a great teacher,
and maybe in particular

00:04:06.550 --> 00:04:07.600
a great science teacher?

00:04:07.600 --> 00:04:09.230
BILL NYE: Passion.

00:04:09.230 --> 00:04:09.730
Passion.

00:04:09.730 --> 00:04:10.646
No, that's what it is.

00:04:10.646 --> 00:04:12.630
What did you like about
your favorite teacher?

00:04:12.630 --> 00:04:15.130
It was he or she was excited
about whatever the hell it was,

00:04:15.130 --> 00:04:16.149
right?

00:04:16.149 --> 00:04:19.230
Whatever the heck it was, sorry.

00:04:19.230 --> 00:04:24.110
So you want to have
passion, and you also

00:04:24.110 --> 00:04:27.610
want the person to
be knowledgeable.

00:04:27.610 --> 00:04:29.111
It's very troubling
when you show up

00:04:29.111 --> 00:04:30.610
and you feel like,
he doesn't really

00:04:30.610 --> 00:04:31.960
know what he's talking about.

00:04:31.960 --> 00:04:34.090
Sort of story of my life.

00:04:34.090 --> 00:04:37.740
But it's the passion
and the subject matter

00:04:37.740 --> 00:04:39.200
that interests you.

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:40.594
That's what makes
a good teacher.

00:04:40.594 --> 00:04:42.010
DANA HAN-KLEIN:
Is there something

00:04:42.010 --> 00:04:43.930
you think we can do as
a society in general

00:04:43.930 --> 00:04:47.616
to encourage the next generation
of passionate teachers?

00:04:47.616 --> 00:04:49.615
Because they're the ones
sort of leading the way

00:04:49.615 --> 00:04:53.280
for the future of our future.

00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:56.080
BILL NYE: I just tell you guys,
and this is not rocket surgery,

00:04:56.080 --> 00:04:58.580
you just have to pay teachers.

00:04:58.580 --> 00:04:59.870
No way.

00:04:59.870 --> 00:05:01.010
Sorry.

00:05:01.010 --> 00:05:04.530
If a person coming out
of engineering school

00:05:04.530 --> 00:05:06.470
could get a job as
a physics teacher

00:05:06.470 --> 00:05:11.290
instead of writing code here,
he would think twice, right?

00:05:11.290 --> 00:05:14.450
Well, what do you make, four,
five times as much money

00:05:14.450 --> 00:05:18.060
at Google as you do
teaching in high school?

00:05:18.060 --> 00:05:22.180
So it just makes people
make different choices.

00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:25.500
And apparently-- this is
anecdotal-- but apparently

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:28.150
in my parents' day
that wasn't the case.

00:05:28.150 --> 00:05:32.720
And so teaching was
considered a profession

00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:34.410
and people were well paid.

00:05:34.410 --> 00:05:37.280
But since so many
public school systems

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:43.000
are tied to property
taxes, you end up

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.400
with the people who need the
best teachers getting the worst

00:05:46.400 --> 00:05:49.520
teachers, or the least qualified
teachers of the teachers who

00:05:49.520 --> 00:05:51.280
are into it.

00:05:51.280 --> 00:05:52.940
And so on and so on.

00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:55.460
But this is the United States.

00:05:55.460 --> 00:05:56.920
And so I was born here.

00:05:56.920 --> 00:05:58.680
I don't know any better.

00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:00.480
I want the United
States to be the world

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:01.940
leader in all this stuff.

00:06:01.940 --> 00:06:03.740
You can't help it.

00:06:03.740 --> 00:06:05.550
Any Canadian people?

00:06:05.550 --> 00:06:06.770
Right on.

00:06:06.770 --> 00:06:08.830
See?

00:06:08.830 --> 00:06:10.980
It's an example
of some socialism

00:06:10.980 --> 00:06:12.570
that works very well, right?

00:06:12.570 --> 00:06:14.880
Seems to work very well.

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:18.880
So seems like solvable problems.

00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:19.630
I ramble.

00:06:19.630 --> 00:06:20.660
Imagine.

00:06:20.660 --> 00:06:21.260
Weird.

00:06:21.260 --> 00:06:22.760
DANA HAN-KLEIN:
It's still on topic.

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:24.171
BILL NYE: A little bit.

00:06:24.171 --> 00:06:26.670
DANA HAN-KLEIN: So would you
say you value most in education

00:06:26.670 --> 00:06:27.660
is the passion?

00:06:27.660 --> 00:06:30.090
And obviously the
ground-level knowledge

00:06:30.090 --> 00:06:33.460
that's required to teach this
information to other people.

00:06:33.460 --> 00:06:35.775
Are there other parts
of it that you value?

00:06:35.775 --> 00:06:37.400
BILL NYE: Well, the
other thing is, you

00:06:37.400 --> 00:06:39.394
know-- does anybody have kids?

00:06:39.394 --> 00:06:40.560
You've met people with kids.

00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:43.220
Some of you were kids.

00:06:43.220 --> 00:06:50.270
And kids, after a fashion,
respond well to rules.

00:06:50.270 --> 00:06:54.810
And I would say they respond
well to expectations.

00:06:54.810 --> 00:06:57.830
And as a friend of mine
says, there are no rules.

00:06:57.830 --> 00:07:01.400
There are traditions
and understandings.

00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:03.684
So yeah, if you screw
up, we have a tradition

00:07:03.684 --> 00:07:04.600
of you being punished.

00:07:07.920 --> 00:07:10.480
I think that-- you know
that feeling where you

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:12.890
want to do well for a teacher?

00:07:12.890 --> 00:07:15.330
You want to achieve
something for a teacher?

00:07:15.330 --> 00:07:18.460
That's because he or she
has set out expectations.

00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:21.580
We're going to have this many
quizzes or homework assignments

00:07:21.580 --> 00:07:23.950
or term papers or
whatever the heck it is.

00:07:23.950 --> 00:07:26.530
And you want to meet
those expectations.

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:30.350
But you don't want rules for
the sake of rules, right?

00:07:30.350 --> 00:07:32.960
So part of it, part of
being a good teacher

00:07:32.960 --> 00:07:36.280
or a successful
educator is to set

00:07:36.280 --> 00:07:38.772
achievable goals, expectations.

00:07:38.772 --> 00:07:41.230
DANA HAN-KLEIN: Would you say
that setting achievable goals

00:07:41.230 --> 00:07:42.960
and expectations is
something that we,

00:07:42.960 --> 00:07:45.370
more in the current fields,
that we sort of need

00:07:45.370 --> 00:07:47.630
to step up and become
leaders in again,

00:07:47.630 --> 00:07:51.420
with engineering and science
fields and mathematics?

00:07:51.420 --> 00:07:53.790
Or do we need to make
it more accessible?

00:07:53.790 --> 00:07:55.540
BILL NYE: Well,
as I say, you have

00:07:55.540 --> 00:07:58.160
to do everything all at once.

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:01.560
So you have to make it
achievable and accessible.

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:03.800
But it's really
easy to set goals

00:08:03.800 --> 00:08:05.740
that the students can't meet.

00:08:05.740 --> 00:08:07.280
It's really easy.

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:10.950
And if you set the bar
too low as an educator,

00:08:10.950 --> 00:08:11.840
you're frustrated.

00:08:11.840 --> 00:08:13.890
I should have asked
more of these people.

00:08:13.890 --> 00:08:21.460
So how many people
are a product of STEM?

00:08:21.460 --> 00:08:22.030
STEM.

00:08:22.030 --> 00:08:23.821
Science, Technology,
Engineering, and Math.

00:08:23.821 --> 00:08:27.120
How many people got out
of school before all that?

00:08:27.120 --> 00:08:28.330
Yeah.

00:08:28.330 --> 00:08:34.330
So for people my
age, we didn't have

00:08:34.330 --> 00:08:38.440
that sort of background
noise of STEM, STEM, STEM,

00:08:38.440 --> 00:08:41.929
because we had
the space program.

00:08:41.929 --> 00:08:45.320
And everybody was just
expecting that people

00:08:45.320 --> 00:08:48.590
would go to the moon, that
cars would have fins on them

00:08:48.590 --> 00:08:50.740
and look like rockets.

00:08:50.740 --> 00:08:55.350
And everybody expected that
great things would be achieved.

00:08:55.350 --> 00:09:01.310
But after that, after the Cold
War sort of resolved itself,

00:09:01.310 --> 00:09:03.870
then that emphasis fell off.

00:09:03.870 --> 00:09:07.520
So the big challenge now
is not going to the moon.

00:09:07.520 --> 00:09:09.740
It's going to be climate change.

00:09:09.740 --> 00:09:14.790
And so I want you all to be
the next great generation.

00:09:14.790 --> 00:09:18.720
Both of my parents are
buried, or interred,

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:20.300
at Arlington Cemetery.

00:09:20.300 --> 00:09:22.150
They were both in World War II.

00:09:22.150 --> 00:09:26.000
By the way, if you get a chance
to spend four years in prisoner

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.668
of war camp, don't do it.

00:09:29.668 --> 00:09:30.167
Don't do it.

00:09:33.840 --> 00:09:35.419
DANA HAN-KLEIN: Sound advice.

00:09:35.419 --> 00:09:35.960
Sound advice.

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:40.610
BILL NYE: If it's an opportunity
that you're confronted with.

00:09:40.610 --> 00:09:43.340
Then ladies, I just
gotta tell you.

00:09:43.340 --> 00:09:47.390
So how many people have seen
"Imitation Game?" right?

00:09:47.390 --> 00:09:50.790
It's got your very good-looking
Benny Bob Cumberbatch there.

00:09:50.790 --> 00:09:53.045
DANA HAN-KLEIN: Something
along those lines.

00:09:53.045 --> 00:09:55.420
BILL NYE: I mean, I have no
problem with Keira Knightley.

00:09:55.420 --> 00:09:55.920
I'm good.

00:09:55.920 --> 00:09:58.460
I'm good.

00:09:58.460 --> 00:10:02.060
The whole thing there took
place in Britain in that movie.

00:10:02.060 --> 00:10:06.022
Well, my mother was graduated
from Goucher College

00:10:06.022 --> 00:10:07.230
back when we had such things.

00:10:07.230 --> 00:10:09.920
It was the sister
school to Johns Hopkins

00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:12.430
in Baltimore, Maryland.

00:10:12.430 --> 00:10:16.240
And so the dean of
students was a woman

00:10:16.240 --> 00:10:18.090
named Dorothy
Stimson, who happened

00:10:18.090 --> 00:10:20.990
to be the first cousin
of Henry Stimson, who

00:10:20.990 --> 00:10:22.910
was the Secretary of War.

00:10:22.910 --> 00:10:27.490
This was back before it was
called Secretary of Defense.

00:10:27.490 --> 00:10:31.130
It was called war, like
that's what we're doing here.

00:10:31.130 --> 00:10:33.551
And I often wonder if
things would be different,

00:10:33.551 --> 00:10:36.050
