AUDIENCE: Hello, Bill Nye.

00:55:36.070 --> 00:55:37.720
My name is Tien.

00:55:37.720 --> 00:55:43.370
My question is, do you think
that mankind will eventually

00:55:43.370 --> 00:55:46.770
move to space, where kids
are born and raised in space?

00:55:46.770 --> 00:55:49.810
And if so, how much longer
do you think it will take?

00:55:49.810 --> 00:55:52.389
BILL NYE: Now when you say
mankind, you mean humankind.

00:55:52.389 --> 00:55:53.180
I'm looking at you.

00:55:53.180 --> 00:55:56.045
I don't know you, but I think
you want to go humankind.

00:55:59.560 --> 00:56:03.200
So this is a great question.

00:56:03.200 --> 00:56:07.020
It leads to a bigger, higher
idea that I'm all into right

00:56:07.020 --> 00:56:08.400
now.

00:56:08.400 --> 00:56:12.210
We grew up-- especially in the
US, we grew up with this idea

00:56:12.210 --> 00:56:13.350
that you just keep going.

00:56:13.350 --> 00:56:14.480
You just keep moving.

00:56:14.480 --> 00:56:18.750
In fact, humankind--
everybody's from East Africa.

00:56:18.750 --> 00:56:20.240
Everybody.

00:56:20.240 --> 00:56:22.700
Let's go, we'll
go to Mesopotamia.

00:56:22.700 --> 00:56:25.120
Hey, we found some plants
that grow every year.

00:56:25.120 --> 00:56:25.870
Let's eat those.

00:56:25.870 --> 00:56:26.500
Cool.

00:56:26.500 --> 00:56:29.490
Wheat and corn and
all this stuff.

00:56:29.490 --> 00:56:29.990
OK.

00:56:29.990 --> 00:56:30.400
Cool.

00:56:30.400 --> 00:56:30.980
We'll stay here for awhile.

00:56:30.980 --> 00:56:33.010
It's nice here, but
I'm going to go.

00:56:33.010 --> 00:56:33.650
I hate you.

00:56:33.650 --> 00:56:35.230
I'm going east.

00:56:35.230 --> 00:56:37.440
And then people
go across Eurasia,

00:56:37.440 --> 00:56:40.800
and they end up in India.

00:56:40.800 --> 00:56:46.140
They get so out of hand they
end up in Alaska and then all

00:56:46.140 --> 00:56:49.930
down North America, kicking
mammal butt all the way down,

00:56:49.930 --> 00:56:51.757
eating everything.

00:56:51.757 --> 00:56:53.840
But we're not going to be
able to do that forever.

00:56:53.840 --> 00:56:56.196
We're going to run out of earth.

00:56:56.196 --> 00:56:57.570
And so I think
it's going to take

00:56:57.570 --> 00:57:00.990
a change in our world view.

00:57:00.990 --> 00:57:04.500
Living and dying in space
sounds cool and romantic and

00:57:04.500 --> 00:57:06.480
consistent with this,
let's spread out,

00:57:06.480 --> 00:57:09.050
let's take over the
world, the universe,

00:57:09.050 --> 00:57:10.050
I mean the solar system.

00:57:10.050 --> 00:57:12.040
I think it's really difficult.

00:57:12.040 --> 00:57:13.610
I mean, I'll give
you that humans

00:57:13.610 --> 00:57:15.290
live in extraordinary places.

00:57:15.290 --> 00:57:18.000
But everywhere-- I
mean, by our standards

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:20.040
here in northern California.

00:57:20.040 --> 00:57:23.640
Does everybody know the
motto of California?

00:57:23.640 --> 00:57:26.022
The state motto, my
fellow Californians?

00:57:26.022 --> 00:57:26.980
DANA HAN-KLEIN: Eureka.

00:57:26.980 --> 00:57:27.688
BILL NYE: Eureka.

00:57:27.688 --> 00:57:29.320
Yeah, I found it.

00:57:29.320 --> 00:57:32.750
So these European guys
come over the hill.

00:57:32.750 --> 00:57:37.390
Orange trees are like weeds and
the salmon are in the river.

00:57:37.390 --> 00:57:39.360
They're like in the
Sacramento River like this.

00:57:39.360 --> 00:57:42.100
It's all the protein
you'd ever want, right?

00:57:42.100 --> 00:57:44.500
And it's so out of hand.

00:57:44.500 --> 00:57:48.000
In California the
rocks are made of gold.

00:57:48.000 --> 00:57:51.060
The thing is so crazy.

00:57:51.060 --> 00:57:54.330
But in zero gravity
on Mars, places

00:57:54.330 --> 00:57:55.890
like that, it's not like that.

00:57:55.890 --> 00:57:59.070
Like when you open the
spacecraft door on Mars,

00:57:59.070 --> 00:58:01.680
you're going to
notice right away.

00:58:01.680 --> 00:58:04.797
Really cold, and
you can't breathe.

00:58:04.797 --> 00:58:05.880
You'll notice that, right?

00:58:05.880 --> 00:58:07.390
That not breathing part.

00:58:07.390 --> 00:58:09.940
You'll really be
focused on that.

00:58:09.940 --> 00:58:13.570
So it sounds
romantic, but I think

00:58:13.570 --> 00:58:17.320
what our future is going to
be is exploring these places,

00:58:17.320 --> 00:58:20.680
but nurturing, taking care
of ecosystems here on earth.

00:58:20.680 --> 00:58:24.620
This could be Bill the Hippie
talking, who's lost his way,

00:58:24.620 --> 00:58:26.900
is an old curmudgeon.

00:58:26.900 --> 00:58:32.490
But living in space and having
babies in space-- making

00:58:32.490 --> 00:58:35.320
babies, I think,
is probably cool.

00:58:35.320 --> 00:58:37.710
But having babies--
you know, there

00:58:37.710 --> 00:58:39.290
was a couple on
the space shuttle,

00:58:39.290 --> 00:58:43.020
and NASA's all, no comment.

00:58:43.020 --> 00:58:46.080
You've got to think, though.

00:58:46.080 --> 00:58:47.059
You've got to think.

00:58:47.059 --> 00:58:48.850
DANA HAN-KLEIN:
Off-the-record experiments.

00:58:48.850 --> 00:58:50.160
BILL NYE: So far.

00:58:50.160 --> 00:58:52.920
But maybe there'll be a "now
it can be told" someday,

00:58:52.920 --> 00:58:55.219
some book.

00:58:55.219 --> 00:58:56.885
And I imagine there's
some complexities.

00:58:59.900 --> 00:59:04.020
I've spent a lot
of time imagining.

00:59:04.020 --> 00:59:06.560
DANA HAN-KLEIN:
But back to humans.

00:59:06.560 --> 00:59:10.660
BILL NYE: But I think it's
a lot harder than it looks.

00:59:10.660 --> 00:59:13.690
It is a cool thing to
ponder, what would it

00:59:13.690 --> 00:59:14.786
be like to live in space?

00:59:14.786 --> 00:59:17.160
And I'll just tell you from
a science fiction standpoint,

00:59:17.160 --> 00:59:20.090
"2001" is still a
cool movie where

00:59:20.090 --> 00:59:23.270
they create a little bit
of artificial gravity.

00:59:23.270 --> 00:59:26.536
When we go to Mars, I think
we're going to need to do that.

00:59:26.536 --> 00:59:28.160
Well, you can take
pills and everything

00:59:28.160 --> 00:59:29.610
and exercise eight hours a day.

00:59:29.610 --> 00:59:32.380
I know, but I think we're
going to want to have something

00:59:32.380 --> 00:59:34.840
that spins sooner or later.

00:59:34.840 --> 00:59:35.901
It's a great question.

00:59:35.901 --> 00:59:36.650
I don't know, man.

00:59:36.650 --> 00:59:37.340
Wo-man.

00:59:37.340 --> 00:59:38.380
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:59:38.380 --> 00:59:39.296
BILL NYE: Tien, right?

00:59:39.296 --> 00:59:40.270
I don't know, Tien.

00:59:40.270 --> 00:59:40.770
Yes.

00:59:40.770 --> 00:59:42.670
MALE SPEAKER: So
we have a question

00:59:42.670 --> 00:59:45.300
from Googlers on
the live stream.

00:59:45.300 --> 00:59:47.210
Kathleen is
wondering, as a child

00:59:47.210 --> 00:59:49.760
I participated in Mad
Science and really enjoyed

00:59:49.760 --> 00:59:52.850
that experience, but didn't
find any programs like this

00:59:52.850 --> 00:59:54.490
after middle school years.

00:59:54.490 --> 00:59:56.060
What are some ways
you think science

00:59:56.060 --> 01:00:00.560
can gain more participation
from high schoolers and beyond?

01:00:00.560 --> 01:00:05.030
BILL NYE: You at Google
ought to have a program, man.

01:00:05.030 --> 01:00:07.850
I don't know, except
I do a job every year

01:00:07.850 --> 01:00:11.560
for Toshiba and the National
Science Teachers Association.

01:00:11.560 --> 01:00:12.960
I'm not saying
this is a panacea.

01:00:12.960 --> 01:00:15.880
This is something
to think about.

01:00:15.880 --> 01:00:18.590
It's a scholarship program
called ExploraVision

01:00:18.590 --> 01:00:21.850
where you have to come up
with an idea for an invention

01:00:21.850 --> 01:00:26.130
that you think will come into
existence in the next 20 years.

01:00:26.130 --> 01:00:30.490
And what's cool about it,
there are high school awards

01:00:30.490 --> 01:00:35.030
akin to the Intel
Science Awards and so on.

01:00:35.030 --> 01:00:37.240
But it starts in kindergarten.

01:00:37.240 --> 01:00:40.835
So a program like
Mad Science that

01:00:40.835 --> 01:00:42.800
starts in kindergarten
through second grade,

01:00:42.800 --> 01:00:48.110
then third through fifth, and
sixth through eighth, and then

01:00:48.110 --> 01:00:51.630
high school, it's consistent
all the way through.

01:00:51.630 --> 01:00:53.300
So I guess here's
what I think, is

01:00:53.300 --> 01:00:57.160
we should find ways to build
on existing things like Mad

01:00:57.160 --> 01:00:58.300
Science.

01:00:58.300 --> 01:01:01.060
And I guess I would call on
a corporation like Google

01:01:01.060 --> 01:01:02.820
to lead the way.

01:01:02.820 --> 01:01:05.200
I mean, heck, I had
sushi in the lunchroom

01:01:05.200 --> 01:01:06.732
today, for crying out loud.

01:01:06.732 --> 01:01:08.420
DANA HAN-KLEIN: In a boat?

01:01:08.420 --> 01:01:09.520
BILL NYE: In a boat.

01:01:09.520 --> 01:01:10.620
Yes, a miniature boat.

01:01:10.620 --> 01:01:12.220
DANA HAN-KLEIN: The sushi was
in a boat, not the people.

01:01:12.220 --> 01:01:13.120
BILL NYE: Yeah.

01:01:13.120 --> 01:01:15.860
Yeah, we weren't in a boat.

01:01:15.860 --> 01:01:17.180
No, it was solid ground.

01:01:17.180 --> 01:01:19.010
Yeah.

01:01:19.010 --> 01:01:22.250
I mean, I get a little dizzy,
but it wasn't in a boat.

01:01:22.250 --> 01:01:24.740
But there's a miniature
boat on the table

01:01:24.740 --> 01:01:29.320
with a miniature fishing net
with miniature fishing weights.

01:01:29.320 --> 01:01:31.050
It was cool.

01:01:31.050 --> 01:01:32.720
It was really cool,
and thank you.

01:01:32.720 --> 01:01:33.670
Really appreciate it.

01:01:33.670 --> 01:01:35.230
It was cool.

